WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.646 --> 00:00:03.520
STEVE GROVE: Good morning
and good afternoon.

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:04.420
My name Steve Grove.

00:00:04.420 --> 00:00:06.827
I look after a team here at
Google called the News Lab.

00:00:06.827 --> 00:00:07.910
We're actually a new team.

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:08.930
About a year old.

00:00:08.930 --> 00:00:12.374
We're focused on innovation
in the media landscape.

00:00:12.374 --> 00:00:13.790
But before that,
I actually worked

00:00:13.790 --> 00:00:16.165
at YouTube, which is where I
first came across David Evan

00:00:16.165 --> 00:00:17.900
Harris and the
Global Lives project,

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:20.450
which you're all here today to
learn a little bit more about.

00:00:20.450 --> 00:00:23.390
It's really, really a unique
project in the media landscape

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:23.890
today.

00:00:23.890 --> 00:00:26.810
We're very pleased to have
David and Naomi joining us here

00:00:26.810 --> 00:00:28.340
in Mountain View for this talk.

00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:29.920
How many of you have
seen the exhibit

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:33.747
in the lobby of building 43
before coming to this talk?

00:00:33.747 --> 00:00:34.330
Show of hands.

00:00:34.330 --> 00:00:35.200
Anybody?

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:36.080
Just a few.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:36.580
OK.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:36.810
Great.

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:38.226
So this will be
the perfect tee up

00:00:38.226 --> 00:00:40.900
for you to go actually
observe the exhibit yourself.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:43.125
It's right inside the
front lobby of Google.

00:00:43.125 --> 00:00:45.390
And it's really a
phenomenal exhibit.

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:48.530
It has over 500 hours of
footage from the daily life

00:00:48.530 --> 00:00:51.496
of 20 people in seven
different countries.

00:00:51.496 --> 00:00:52.370
And it's really neat.

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:54.485
It's sort of an eight
screen immersive experience

00:00:54.485 --> 00:00:56.610
where you get to hear both
the audio and the visual

00:00:56.610 --> 00:00:59.280
from lives of these people that
David and Naomi and others have

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:00.664
documented around the world.

00:01:00.664 --> 00:01:03.080
And they'll be up here to tell
you about it in just a bit.

00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:06.350
Google is just one place this
exhibit has found itself.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:08.950
It has also been at the
Smithsonian, the United Nations

00:01:08.950 --> 00:01:09.680
University.

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:13.040
I think it originally debuted
at the Yerba Buena Art Center

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:14.730
up in San Francisco.

00:01:14.730 --> 00:01:17.220
So as I mentioned, I
first met David back

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:20.100
when I was at YouTube
in about 2007.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:24.200
This was a long time ago
in internet video years.

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:28.280
This was back when Lonely
Girl 13 was a huge phenomenon.

00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:32.210
When one of the original viral
videos on the web was a video

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:35.050
called Lazy Sunday from
Saturday Night Live.

00:01:35.050 --> 00:01:36.732
If anyone remembers that.

00:01:36.732 --> 00:01:38.440
In terms of my own
experience at YouTube,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:40.648
it was around the same time
that YouTube just started

00:01:40.648 --> 00:01:41.770
to be used for politics.

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:44.400
So if you remember George
Allen being caught on a camera

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:48.330
calling his campaign opponent's
videographer a macaca,

00:01:48.330 --> 00:01:50.840
that moment being captured,
uploaded to YouTube.

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:52.300
It went viral.

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:55.205
He then lost a very
close race in many ways

00:01:55.205 --> 00:01:56.080
because of that clip.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:57.990
And sort of YouTube
politics had been born.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:01.450
So YouTube has been used in a
lot of ways since that point.

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:03.580
But David was one of these
really early guys who

00:02:03.580 --> 00:02:06.390
I think really recognized
the potential of online video

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:09.039
to really transform how we
understand the world around us.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:12.110
And I think most importantly,
how we understand the lives

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:14.460
of others who don't
live right next door,

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:18.200
or in the same state, or
even in the same country.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:20.790
I think when he set aside to
do the Global Lives Project--

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:23.570
and he'll you a little bit
more about it when it comes up.

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:25.545
He didn't want to just go out
there and say, hey, check out

00:02:25.545 --> 00:02:26.920
these documentary
films of people

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:29.420
who live around the world and
have different experiences

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:29.920
to you.

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:32.330
He wanted to do it in
a really unique way.

00:02:32.330 --> 00:02:37.040
What you see in these film is
a really raw, unvarnished look

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:39.390
at what it's like to
live somewhere else.

00:02:39.390 --> 00:02:41.540
He takes the idea
of day in the life,

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:42.980
and he takes it very literally.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:45.855
It is an actual day in the
life of these individuals

00:02:45.855 --> 00:02:49.300
that he goes out and
films 24 hours straight.

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:50.830
Camera runs for
the whole 24 hours.

00:02:50.830 --> 00:02:52.370
They get a full
picture of what it's

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:54.710
like to be in that
person's shoes.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:56.560
And it helps you
answer questions--

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:58.290
to use some of
David's examples--

00:02:58.290 --> 00:03:00.340
like what does a
Brazilian rapper do

00:03:00.340 --> 00:03:01.920
first thing in the morning?

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:04.740
Or how long does it take
a Palestinian refugee

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:06.640
to walk to dance class?

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:09.780
Or what's it like to get
around the Tokyo subway

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:11.830
when you have to
use a wheelchair?

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:13.650
These are some really
ordinary moments

00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:16.364
from which David extracts really
extraordinary stories that

00:03:16.364 --> 00:03:18.780
give us a real sense of what
life is like around the world

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:20.140
today.

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:22.480
The program really got
kicking about five years ago,

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:24.524
thanks to several
grants from the National

00:03:24.524 --> 00:03:25.482
Endowment for the Arts.

00:03:25.482 --> 00:03:27.344
Three years ago,
David took the program

00:03:27.344 --> 00:03:29.385
and made it not just about
the videos themselves,

00:03:29.385 --> 00:03:30.794
but a curriculum.

00:03:30.794 --> 00:03:32.960
For those of you who saw
these booklets on the table

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:35.260
when you came in, this is a
fully immersive curriculum

00:03:35.260 --> 00:03:36.080
for schools to use.

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:38.480
Over 1,000 teachers have
this in their classrooms,

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:40.810
and can use it showing
videos from these films,

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:43.200
but also a lot of great
questions and answers.

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.880
And a deep curriculum
that David developed

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:48.900
with a group at
Stanford to bring

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:51.580
this work to the classroom.

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:54.220
And when I think
about this project,

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:55.920
it's one of these
things where it's

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:57.795
sort of like private
sector/public diplomacy.

00:03:57.795 --> 00:04:00.090
If you talk to somebody
at the State Department,

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:01.960
or any foreign
government about what

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:04.420
it means to understand
cultures around the world, one

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:06.170
of the first things
they always talk about

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.449
is like well, if you could
do an educational exchange,

00:04:08.449 --> 00:04:10.490
or if you could meet
someone from someplace else,

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:12.840
they no longer seem
like the other.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:15.891
But they seem like, you know--
you see a notion of sameness,

00:04:15.891 --> 00:04:16.390
right?

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:18.029
And that gives you
a new perspective,

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:20.446
I think, empathetic perspective
about the world around you

00:04:20.446 --> 00:04:21.278
that's so important.

00:04:21.278 --> 00:04:23.560
It's why we're so excited
to have David and Naomi here

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:24.510
with us today.

00:04:24.510 --> 00:04:27.360
He is joined as
well by Naomi Ture.

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:30.869
She filmed the Vietnam
portion of this exhibit.

00:04:30.869 --> 00:04:32.660
She'll tell you all
about that in a moment.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:34.580
She's an accomplished filmmaker.

00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:37.445
She recently just finished the
project of "Batkid Begins."

00:04:37.445 --> 00:04:40.070
How many of you sort of followed
the whole phenomenon of Batkid

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:40.950
in San Francisco?

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:43.320
So Naomi just finished
a film with Time Warner

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:46.142
on that extraordinary story.

00:04:46.142 --> 00:04:48.100
She's also been a board
member for Global Lives

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:48.961
for several years.

00:04:48.961 --> 00:04:51.460
I'm going to bring up David now
to give us a quick overview.

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:52.710
David's a sociologist.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:53.410
He's an artist.

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:54.380
He's a curator.

00:04:54.380 --> 00:04:56.880
He founded this program, like
I said, way ahead of its time,

00:04:56.880 --> 00:04:58.504
before online video
was really a thing.

00:04:58.504 --> 00:05:00.419
Back in 2004.

00:05:00.419 --> 00:05:02.710
In addition to running this
extraordinary organization,

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:05.120
he's also a Fellow at the
Institute for the Future,

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:06.850
which means he
knows what's coming.

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.230
So maybe we can get
to that in the Q&amp;A.

00:05:09.230 --> 00:05:11.410
He also was on the staff
at UC Berkeley's Haas

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:12.850
School of Business.

00:05:12.850 --> 00:05:14.420
He started out
earlier in his career

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:15.795
at the White House
on the Council

00:05:15.795 --> 00:05:18.070
on Environmental Quality,
and spent a lot of time

00:05:18.070 --> 00:05:21.346
in Sao Paulo, where he
got his sociology degree.

