by your employer, Google.

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:50.781
So with that, let me show you
some footage from Vietnam.

00:22:50.781 --> 00:22:52.739
And then we'll talk a
little bit more about it.

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:06.980
[SPEAKING VIETNAMESE]

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:52.240
STEVE GROVE: Great.

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:53.250
Thank you, David.

00:25:53.250 --> 00:25:54.290
Naomi, why don't you
come up and join us.

00:25:54.290 --> 00:25:55.581
Round of applause for the film.

00:25:55.581 --> 00:26:00.490
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:03.310
So David, let's start with you.

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:06.030
Going back to 2004, what
gave you the inspiration

00:26:06.030 --> 00:26:08.055
to start this whole thing?

00:26:08.055 --> 00:26:09.930
DAVID EVAN HARRIS: So
actually it was in 2002

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:10.850
that I had the idea.

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:12.780
I was in college.

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:15.180
And I was traveling
as part of a study

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:17.670
abroad program where I
had this amazing luck

00:26:17.670 --> 00:26:20.694
to be able to live in
five different countries

00:26:20.694 --> 00:26:21.860
over the course of the year.

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:25.910
And I went to Tanzania, India,
the Philippines, Mexico,

00:26:25.910 --> 00:26:27.000
and the UK.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.370
I lived in a bamboo
house in the Philippines.

00:26:29.370 --> 00:26:32.560
I lived in a former squatter
settlement in Mexico City.

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:35.600
I lived in a mansion with
five servants in New Delhi.

00:26:35.600 --> 00:26:37.740
And that experience is
something I really want

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:40.000
to share with other people.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:44.300
And I then went on to get a
graduate degree in sociology.

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:47.970
But I was feeling like in my
writing, my academic writing,

00:26:47.970 --> 00:26:50.950
it wasn't really getting
across just what you

00:26:50.950 --> 00:26:53.640
can gain from really
spending time one-on-one

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:56.370
or in someone's home
with another person.

00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:57.500
So I wanted to share that.

00:26:57.500 --> 00:27:00.110
That's really where
the idea came from.

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:01.710
It was a very long process.

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:03.400
But that's how we
arrived at that.

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:07.509
But still every week we get
inquiries through our website

00:27:07.509 --> 00:27:09.050
from filmmakers that
want to continue

00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:10.870
adding to the collection.

00:27:10.870 --> 00:27:15.150
And we're looking for ways to
find the resources to continue

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:16.882
producing more and more video.

00:27:16.882 --> 00:27:19.340
STEVE GROVE: Naomi, we just
saw a clip from your experience

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:19.680
in Vietnam.

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:20.740
How long ago was that?

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:22.200
NAOMI TURE: That was like, 2003.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:23.100
STEVE GROVE: 2003.

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:23.820
OK.

00:27:23.820 --> 00:27:24.890
So you're a filmmaker.

00:27:24.890 --> 00:27:27.070
Your traditional process
of filmmaking, I'm sure,

00:27:27.070 --> 00:27:28.380
is documentary style.

00:27:28.380 --> 00:27:28.880
You shoot.

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:29.387
You stop.

00:27:29.387 --> 00:27:30.470
You take a drink of water.

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:31.420
You keep going.

00:27:31.420 --> 00:27:32.380
This is very different.

00:27:32.380 --> 00:27:33.860
You filmed for 24
hours straight.

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:34.982
Tell us what that's like.

00:27:34.982 --> 00:27:35.690
NAOMI TURE: Yeah.

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:37.189
So I think we
mentioned this before.

00:27:37.189 --> 00:27:40.960
But it's really kind of the
ultimate filmmaking challenge.

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:43.790
It's like endurance filmmaking.

00:27:43.790 --> 00:27:51.750
So obviously preparation is
months and months in advance,

00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:53.430
as in any documentary.

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:57.224
But this is a
logistical challenge.

00:27:57.224 --> 00:27:58.640
STEVE GROVE: And
is it you holding

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:00.380
the camera the entire time?

00:28:00.380 --> 00:28:03.493
Like you personally are holding
one camera for 24 hours?

00:28:03.493 --> 00:28:04.243
NAOMI TURE: So no.

00:28:04.243 --> 00:28:05.450
So we definitely had a team.

00:28:05.450 --> 00:28:08.040
So I had a team of seven people.

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:11.770
Four of us were actually
holding the camera.

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:13.080
The cinematographers.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:15.310
And the rest are just support.

00:28:15.310 --> 00:28:18.690
And so logistically,
the way we do it

00:28:18.690 --> 00:28:22.250
is actually Alfred
Hitchcock style.

00:28:22.250 --> 00:28:25.540
So we want the
experience for the viewer

00:28:25.540 --> 00:28:30.430
to feel as though it's a
constant-- we're filming

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:34.820
from when they go to sleep,
their entire sleep, turning

00:28:34.820 --> 00:28:35.810
around in sleep.

00:28:35.810 --> 00:28:36.500
They wake up.

00:28:36.500 --> 00:28:37.590
They brush their teeth.

00:28:37.590 --> 00:28:38.900
They wash their face.

00:28:38.900 --> 00:28:40.090
They're exhausted.

00:28:40.090 --> 00:28:42.860
And then they finally get
their caffeine or whatever they

00:28:42.860 --> 00:28:45.780
need for the morning and go.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:50.430
So because we're filming
every single possible minute,

00:28:50.430 --> 00:28:52.610
and no camera in the world
can film for 24 hours.

00:28:52.610 --> 00:28:54.700
There's no card.

00:28:54.700 --> 00:28:58.490
Well, actually there
are ways to do that.

00:28:58.490 --> 00:29:01.175
But what we needed was, you
need at least two cameras

00:29:01.175 --> 00:29:02.700
and at least two
camera operators.

00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:05.720
So you're constantly signaling
to the other camera operator

00:29:05.720 --> 00:29:07.130
and switching cameras.

00:29:07.130 --> 00:29:13.600
And in order to kind of
transition to the next thing,

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:16.470
you'll move the camera
to maybe a black space

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:18.370
while the next person
begins filming.

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:18.890
STEVE GROVE: What
do you do about

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:20.022
like showers and bathrooms?

00:29:20.022 --> 00:29:21.980
I mean, these people are
living an actual life.

00:29:21.980 --> 00:29:24.420
So doing things they probably
don't want on camera,

00:29:24.420 --> 00:29:24.930
obviously.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:25.638
NAOMI TURE: Yeah.

00:29:25.638 --> 00:29:28.120
We give very little privacy.

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:30.110
But when they do
go to the bathroom,

00:29:30.110 --> 00:29:37.600
then we do allow them to
go behind the closed doors.

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:39.650
STEVE GROVE: We have
this too, if you wanna.

00:29:39.650 --> 00:29:41.400
NAOMI TURE: On the
boat in Vietnam though,

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:42.860
the bathroom is open to the sky.

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:46.400
So all of us, crew, onscreen
participant, all of us

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:52.270
had to just go in a box
that then would flush right

00:29:52.270 --> 00:29:55.920
into the river, which you then
later on pulled up the river

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:58.451
water to wash the dishes.

00:29:58.451 --> 00:30:00.111
STEVE GROVE: Fascinating.

00:30:00.111 --> 00:30:01.360
So you're given an assignment.

00:30:01.360 --> 00:30:02.200
Tell me how it works.

00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:04.658
You're given an assignment from
David and team, or whoever,

00:30:04.658 --> 00:30:05.610
to go to Vietnam.

00:30:05.610 --> 00:30:08.010
How early in advance--
are you like contacting

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:11.940
a potential subject of your
film months in advance?

00:30:11.940 --> 00:30:14.565
Or how does this work in terms
of approaching the people

00:30:14.565 --> 00:30:15.440
you're gonna profile?

00:30:15.440 --> 00:30:16.148
NAOMI TURE: Yeah.

00:30:16.148 --> 00:30:19.179
So I was actually behind
the scenes for six years

00:30:19.179 --> 00:30:20.720
before I actually
became a filmmaker.

00:30:20.720 --> 00:30:22.900
So I was on the board, on
the production committee,

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:24.740
and looking at
all the proposals.

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:27.410
So yeah, it's month in advance.

00:30:27.410 --> 00:30:29.940
Every proposals
and actual specific

00:30:29.940 --> 00:30:35.020
person that you've researched,
that the team in that area.

00:30:35.020 --> 00:30:39.500
So my team in Ho Chi Minh City
drove down to rural Vietnam,

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:43.580
right below [INAUDIBLE]
in My Khanh village,

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:46.140
found someone who's
willing to participate.

00:30:46.140 --> 00:30:50.440
And then we assemble.

00:30:50.440 --> 00:30:52.910
STEVE GROVE: I'm interested
in the willing to participate

00:30:52.910 --> 00:30:53.910
moment.

00:30:53.910 --> 00:30:56.890
This woman, Huyen, from
the film that you profiled.

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:59.180
What's the pitch look like?

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:01.810
And what kind of
reactions did you get?

00:31:01.810 --> 00:31:05.330
NAOMI TURE: So actually I
was able to see her reaction,

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:08.370
because we lost our
participant a day

00:31:08.370 --> 00:31:09.990
before we were about to film.

00:31:09.990 --> 00:31:14.030
So we had motorbiked across the
whole city of Ho Chi Minh City,

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:17.010
gathered all of our equipment,
had the production van.

00:31:17.010 --> 00:31:20.200
We were ready to go
down, called [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:20.200 --> 00:31:21.930
who was our original
participant.

00:31:21.930 --> 00:31:25.380
And he said, oh, I'm
really, really sick.

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:27.760
And I can't participate.

00:31:27.760 --> 00:31:29.140
And I've been sent home.

00:31:29.140 --> 00:31:32.170
So I'm no longer on
the boat anymore.

00:31:32.170 --> 00:31:34.600
And so we drove
down to [INAUDIBLE],

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:38.890
which is the largest city
in the Mekong River delta

00:31:38.890 --> 00:31:41.480
region in Vietnam to
find another participant.

00:31:41.480 --> 00:31:45.480
And so we split up into
teams of people, each one

00:31:45.480 --> 00:31:47.700
with a Vietnamese local.

00:31:47.700 --> 00:31:51.530
And we went from boat
to boat asking, hey,

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:54.650
would you be willing to be
filmed for 24 hours tomorrow

00:31:54.650 --> 00:31:57.270
morning starting at 5:00 AM?

00:31:57.270 --> 00:32:00.250
And so of course, that's
an interesting question.

00:32:00.250 --> 00:32:04.180
And I think the response
was always positive

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:07.590
because people are
interested in revealing

00:32:07.590 --> 00:32:08.810
something of themselves.

00:32:08.810 --> 00:32:09.310
You know.

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:16.830
And I think we all want
to share in this idea

00:32:16.830 --> 00:32:19.260
of like kind of
global connectedness

00:32:19.260 --> 00:32:20.520
and global empathy.

00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:24.670
And so we had a lot
of positive responses.

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:27.580
The issue was that we
had to find someone

00:32:27.580 --> 00:32:31.100
of a certain age demographic, of
a certain religion, et cetera.

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:32.600
STEVE GROVE: David,
do you find this

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:34.820
to be true in most of the
situations in which you're

00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:38.630
filming these 24-hour shoot,
that people are surprisingly

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:40.540
willing to do it?

00:32:40.540 --> 00:32:42.340
DAVID EVAN HARRIS:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:32:42.340 --> 00:32:44.530
That's a question that comes up.

00:32:44.530 --> 00:32:48.820
And another piece of it
is that the filmmakers are

00:32:48.820 --> 00:32:50.200
surprisingly willing to do it.

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:54.070
The filmmakers-- Naomi
volunteered her time.

00:32:54.070 --> 00:32:57.690
And she, like many of
our other filmmakers,

00:32:57.690 --> 00:32:59.730
went to some significant
personal expense

00:32:59.730 --> 00:33:02.330
to be able to produce
a Global Lives shoot.

00:33:02.330 --> 00:33:06.480
And in many ways this is just
a scaled-up version of someone

00:33:06.480 --> 00:33:08.730
who's a really passionate
Wikipedia contributor

00:33:08.730 --> 00:33:10.450
and spends months
writing articles.

00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:10.950
Right?

00:33:10.950 --> 00:33:13.990
It's someone who
believes in the totality

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:15.430
of this global project.

00:33:15.430 --> 00:33:17.140
And so they're
willing to really put

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:21.020
a lot of blood, sweat, and
tears, and sometimes money

00:33:21.020 --> 00:33:21.660
into that.

00:33:21.660 --> 00:33:25.567
And I think that the
onscreen participants, which

00:33:25.567 --> 00:33:27.900
is the name we use for the
people whose lives we record,

00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:29.710
we say that because
they are really

00:33:29.710 --> 00:33:35.960
participating by giving us their
life and access to their life.

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:38.720
I think all of
them that I've met,

00:33:38.720 --> 00:33:41.890
and the ones that I've
heard about and talked to,

00:33:41.890 --> 00:33:44.340
and heard interviews
with, I think

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:47.520
have an understanding of
what Global Lives is about.

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:51.000
I think it helps that we're
a nonprofit organization,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.520
that we're independent, that
we use the Creative Commons

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:55.530
licenses, that all of
the video that we produce

00:33:55.530 --> 00:33:57.470
can be watched for
free on the internet.

00:33:57.470 --> 00:33:59.670
And I think they
understand that they're

00:33:59.670 --> 00:34:01.819
contributing to something.

00:34:01.819 --> 00:34:03.610
STEVE GROVE: Please
join me with questions.

00:34:03.610 --> 00:34:04.535
Justin.

00:34:04.535 --> 00:34:06.410
AUDIENCE: I imagine it's
pretty wild for them

00:34:06.410 --> 00:34:08.841
to have somebody sort of
arrive at their community,

00:34:08.841 --> 00:34:10.507
especially with
equipment in their face.

00:34:10.507 --> 00:34:11.882
What is that sort
of relationship

00:34:11.882 --> 00:34:14.644
like as you arrived
to them [INAUDIBLE],

00:34:14.644 --> 00:34:16.500
having to spend a
lot of time together?

00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:17.320
NAOMI TURE: Yeah.

00:34:17.320 --> 00:34:17.460
No.

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:19.001
That's a really
interesting question,

00:34:19.001 --> 00:34:20.929
because within the
course of 24 hours,

00:34:20.929 --> 00:34:23.210
there is an intimacy
that develops.

00:34:23.210 --> 00:34:26.900
So it's filmmaker
and participants

00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:29.050
don't know each other at first.

00:34:29.050 --> 00:34:29.550
Right?

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:31.750
And we come in.

00:34:31.750 --> 00:34:33.679
There's maybe a little
bit of awkwardness

00:34:33.679 --> 00:34:37.560
in having a camera pointed
at you for hours and hours

00:34:37.560 --> 00:34:38.290
upon time.

00:34:38.290 --> 00:34:40.159
But after a certain
amount of time,

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:42.489
and it might be
three or four hours,

00:34:42.489 --> 00:34:44.239
you kind of get lost in the day.

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:47.590
So you stop thinking about the
fact that you are filmmaker,

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:50.134
and you are observing someone.

00:34:50.134 --> 00:34:52.800
And they stop thinking about the
fact that they're being filmed.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:56.684
And it becomes this kind of
natural day that progresses.

00:34:56.684 --> 00:34:57.490
It has to.

00:34:57.490 --> 00:35:01.660
You cannot act in front
of a film for 24 hours.

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:04.940
And then during
that course of time,

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:06.850
there is subtle
communications that

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:09.840
happen, because
we never use words

00:35:09.840 --> 00:35:11.677
between the filmmaker
and the participant,

00:35:11.677 --> 00:35:13.010
because we're just filming them.

00:35:13.010 --> 00:35:14.720
We are kind of a
fly on the wall.

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:18.560
But at the same time, there's
subtle things that happen.

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:21.390
So for example, Huyen
was cooking lunch.

00:35:21.390 --> 00:35:22.550
You know, I was filming.

00:35:22.550 --> 00:35:24.330
I had an assistant
right next to me.

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:26.580
And as she began
eating, she actually

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:29.940
filled another bowl with rice
and tuna, with fish sauce,

00:35:29.940 --> 00:35:32.105
and she kind of
handed it towards us.

00:35:32.105 --> 00:35:34.230
It was one of those moments
where you kind of break

00:35:34.230 --> 00:35:36.730
the barrier of filmmaker
and participant.

00:35:36.730 --> 00:35:38.540
And it was really beautiful.

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:42.510
By the end of it, we hadn't
spoken much to each other.

00:35:42.510 --> 00:35:43.590
But we were hugging.

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:45.470
We felt like we were
part of her family.

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:46.010
Everything.

00:35:46.010 --> 00:35:47.290
Almost crying.

00:35:47.290 --> 00:35:50.660
And it's just 24 hours that
you spend with this person.

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:53.930
But you become very close in
this very interesting way.

00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:55.100
STEVE GROVE: How well do you
think you got to know her?

00:35:55.100 --> 00:35:56.850
I mean, how well do
you think you can say,

00:35:56.850 --> 00:35:59.720
I feel like I know who this
person is after 24 hours?

00:35:59.720 --> 00:36:05.070
NAOMI TURE: I mean, do
we know anyone that well?

00:36:05.070 --> 00:36:07.530
I think what it is is
you get to know someone

00:36:07.530 --> 00:36:12.140
well enough that the kind
of ideological boundaries

00:36:12.140 --> 00:36:15.730
or the cultural differences
kind of start bleeding away.

00:36:15.730 --> 00:36:17.190
And it's like, OK.

00:36:17.190 --> 00:36:19.730
It's enough to make that
personal connection,

00:36:19.730 --> 00:36:23.060
that personal leap of stepping
out of your own reality

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:24.579
into someone else's reality.

00:36:24.579 --> 00:36:26.870
DAVID EVAN HARRIS: And that's
actually part of the goal

00:36:26.870 --> 00:36:29.450
is when you come to a
Global Lives exhibit

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:31.680
or you come to our
website, that you

00:36:31.680 --> 00:36:34.880
have an experience of seeing a
lot, and hopefully seeing a lot

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:37.340
that that's not familiar to you.

00:36:37.340 --> 00:36:39.110
But also you leave
the exhibit, or you

00:36:39.110 --> 00:36:41.910
leave the website knowing that
you haven't seen everything,

00:36:41.910 --> 00:36:44.510
and that you couldn't
possibly see all of it.

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:49.610
And in many ways that's the
type of attitude about the world

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:53.260
that we hope to bring,
which is a curiosity,

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:54.640
a desire to learn more.

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:57.370
But a certain
humility and knowledge

00:36:57.370 --> 00:37:00.460
that there's a whole lot
more that you really don't

00:37:00.460 --> 00:37:01.580
know and can't know.

