that piece around sort

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:21.320
of the insights that
come out, and sort

00:39:21.320 --> 00:39:23.111
of like you're discovering
sort of the most

00:39:23.111 --> 00:39:24.840
beautiful pieces of culture.

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:30.750
And how can we share that and
take that around the world?

00:39:30.750 --> 00:39:31.800
NAOMI TURE: Yeah.

00:39:31.800 --> 00:39:35.370
I think just even
from the filming

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:39.600
that I did in
Vietnam-- so one thing

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:41.480
that we really try
to do-- and I'm

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:44.230
unique in that I went
to Vietnam to film.

00:39:44.230 --> 00:39:46.060
But I filmed with a local crew.

00:39:46.060 --> 00:39:48.240
So what Global
Lives attempts to do

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:51.860
is get a crew situated
already in that country

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:54.700
to film a participant
within the country.

00:39:54.700 --> 00:39:56.590
So I think that's
important in that you

00:39:56.590 --> 00:39:59.970
have to kind of understand your
own kind of cultural context.

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:03.290
But then the other
thing is that you

00:40:03.290 --> 00:40:07.330
begin questioning your own
assumptions, your own ideology,

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:08.440
your own culture.

00:40:08.440 --> 00:40:10.780
So we had been stressed
out on cell phones

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:12.560
like every second of the day.

00:40:12.560 --> 00:40:14.830
We arrive on the boat.

00:40:14.830 --> 00:40:19.310
And Huyen and her
brother and the worker,

00:40:19.310 --> 00:40:21.650
they didn't say
anything for an hour.

00:40:21.650 --> 00:40:23.760
They're just sitting
helming the boat.

00:40:23.760 --> 00:40:25.130
And that's it.

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:27.480
And so just that
perspective of oh,

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:29.290
they're not online all the time.

00:40:29.290 --> 00:40:31.910
You know, here's a different
perspective of life.

00:40:31.910 --> 00:40:35.100
Or her definition
of success isn't

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:37.100
to reach the top of the ladder.

00:40:37.100 --> 00:40:40.310
Her definition of success
is to help her family,

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:42.750
is to be happy, you know?

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:46.840
So I think the
definition of life

00:40:46.840 --> 00:40:48.552
itself is going to be different.

00:40:48.552 --> 00:40:50.010
And that's what
you begin to learn.

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:53.860
And you begin to learn
that you know what?

00:40:53.860 --> 00:40:56.740
My world view may
not be important

00:40:56.740 --> 00:40:59.420
when it's put into the
context of someone else's,

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:01.770
or the multiple narratives.

00:41:01.770 --> 00:41:03.270
DAVID EVAN HARRIS:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:41:03.270 --> 00:41:05.685
So one of the communities
that I didn't mention that

00:41:05.685 --> 00:41:07.560
much so far that's
involved with Global Lives

00:41:07.560 --> 00:41:09.030
is the translators.

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:11.830
We've had about 1,500
volunteer translators

00:41:11.830 --> 00:41:14.290
from all over the world that
have contributed their time

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:18.720
to subtitling all of this
500 hours or so of footage

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:19.960
that we produced.

00:41:19.960 --> 00:41:22.170
And one of the
translators from Malawi

00:41:22.170 --> 00:41:24.760
was actually living in the UK.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:26.450
And she sent us a story.

00:41:26.450 --> 00:41:30.030
She said that she was raising
a daughter who I think

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:31.460
was around seven years old.

00:41:31.460 --> 00:41:34.870
And she would show her daughter
video from the Global Lives

00:41:34.870 --> 00:41:36.960
shoots that she was subtitling.

00:41:36.960 --> 00:41:39.980
The shoot was from
Malawi where she grew up.

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:42.210
And her daughter, I don't
think, had been to Malawi.

00:41:42.210 --> 00:41:45.490
And using the videos as a tool
to show her daughter what life

00:41:45.490 --> 00:41:48.360
would have been like back home
if she had grown up there,

00:41:48.360 --> 00:41:50.050
which I found was
really touching.

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:53.910
And she also said that for
her, the Global Lives videos

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:56.860
are a way that the
community that she's part of

00:41:56.860 --> 00:42:00.800
can speak to and share
their voice with the world.

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:02.780
And to me that was
really touching.

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:06.310
Now on the education side,
our whole curriculum, again,

00:42:06.310 --> 00:42:09.200
designed at the Stanford
Graduate School of Education.

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:11.480
Steve has a copy right
there behind him.

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:13.130
And there are some here to grab.

00:42:13.130 --> 00:42:14.410
It's called Unheard Stories.

00:42:14.410 --> 00:42:15.990
And it's all about
building empathy

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:17.470
through the Global
Lives project.

00:42:17.470 --> 00:42:20.520
And this was designed by
a group of grad students,

00:42:20.520 --> 00:42:23.810
that they came up with that
idea to focus on empathy.

00:42:23.810 --> 00:42:26.640
They built it around the Common
Core curriculum standards.

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:29.940
And then they came up with
some metrics, which we then

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:32.330
use surveys to
study, to think about

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:35.340
does Global Lives make
students more interested

00:42:35.340 --> 00:42:37.060
in learning another language?

00:42:37.060 --> 00:42:38.670
Does it make students
more interested

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:41.190
in helping someone who
they see who's in trouble?

00:42:41.190 --> 00:42:43.250
Does it make students
feel more like they can

00:42:43.250 --> 00:42:45.394
make a difference in the world?

00:42:45.394 --> 00:42:47.310
And so all of those, in
a number of questions,

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.040
we're seeing
significant increases

00:42:49.040 --> 00:42:51.870
in before and after
watching the videos.

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:53.650
Now from my perspective,
Global Lives

00:42:53.650 --> 00:42:58.320
is a little more about art
and about asking questions

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:00.550
than increasing
numbers of people

00:43:00.550 --> 00:43:01.790
that have certain emotions.

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:04.880
But at the same time, in the
education field which we've now

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:06.930
dipped our toes, and
increasingly a whole leg

00:43:06.930 --> 00:43:11.540
into-- as I fall off the
chair-- those kinds of numbers

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:13.810
and that kind of research
is really important.

